<h2>Montana Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Montana homeowners have access to several valuable incentives that significantly reduce the cost of solar panel and HVAC system installations. The federal Solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar panel installations completed through 2032, with the credit stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total cost of the solar system, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, making it one of the most valuable incentives available.</p>

<p>Montana offers its own Alternative Energy Tax Credit, which provides a tax credit equal to the lesser of the actual cost or \$500 per dwelling for alternative energy systems, including solar panels and qualifying HVAC equipment. While modest compared to the federal credit, this state incentive provides additional savings that help offset installation costs. The credit can be carried forward for up to four years if it exceeds the taxpayer's liability in any given year.</p>

<p>NorthWestern Energy, Montana's largest utility provider, offers several programs that benefit solar and HVAC customers. Their Universal System Benefits Program provides rebates for energy efficiency improvements, including high-efficiency HVAC systems. The utility's net metering program allows solar customers to receive full retail credit for excess electricity generated, effectively using the grid as a battery to store excess summer production for use during winter months. Additionally, NorthWestern Energy offers time-of-use rates in some areas, which can provide additional savings for customers who can shift electricity usage to off-peak hours or who have solar panels generating during peak rate periods.</p>

<p>Local utility cooperatives throughout Montana may offer additional rebates and incentives for energy efficiency improvements and renewable energy installations. Many of these programs are funded through the Universal System Benefits Program and can provide substantial rebates for qualifying equipment. Property tax exemptions are also available for solar energy systems in Montana, ensuring that adding solar panels doesn't increase property tax assessments despite adding value to the home.</p>

